14
0:00:52.26,000 --> 0:00:54,000
in India I don't need to teach a kid that this means

15
0:00:54.713,000 --> 0:00:55,000
"four runs" in cricket.

16
0:00:56.26,000 --> 0:00:58,000
It comes as a part of our everyday learning.

17
0:00:59.716,000 --> 0:01:02,000
So, I am very interested, from the beginning,

18
0:01:03.26,000 --> 0:01:06,000
how our knowledge about everyday objects and gestures,

19
0:01:07.26,000 --> 0:01:08,000
and how we use these objects,

20
0:01:09.26,000 --> 0:01:11,000
can be leveraged to our interactions with the digital world.

21
0:01:12.26,000 --> 0:01:14,000
Rather than using a keyboard and mouse,

22
0:01:15.26,000 --> 0:01:17,000
why can I not use my computer

23
0:01:18.26,000 --> 0:01:2,000
in the same way that I interact in the physical world?

24
0:01:21.26,000 --> 0:01:23,000
So, I started this exploration around eight years back,

25
0:01:24.26,000 --> 0:01:26,000
and it literally started with a mouse on my desk.

26
0:01:27.26,000 --> 0:01:32,000
Rather than using it for my computer, I actually opened it.

27
0:01:33.26,000 --> 0:01:35,000
Most of you might be aware that, in those days,

28
0:01:35.475,000 --> 0:01:37,000
the mouse used to come with a ball inside,

29
0:01:37.499,000 --> 0:01:38,000
and there were two rollers

30
0:01:39.26,000 --> 0:01:41,000
that actually guide the computer where the ball is moving,

31
0:01:42.26,000 --> 0:01:44,000
and, accordingly, where the mouse is moving.

32
0:01:44.38,000 --> 0:01:46,000
So, I was interested in these two rollers,

33
0:01:47.26,000 --> 0:01:5,000
and I actually wanted more, so I borrowed another mouse from a friend --

34
0:01:50.665,000 --> 0:01:51,000
never returned to him --

35
0:01:52.26,000 --> 0:01:53,000
and I now had four rollers.

36
0:01:54.26,000 --> 0:01:56,000
Interestingly, what I did with these rollers is,

37
0:01:57.26,000 --> 0:02:01,000
basically, I took them off of these mouses and then put them in one line.

38
0:02:02.26,000 --> 0:02:04,000
It had some strings and pulleys and some springs.

39
0:02:05.26,000 --> 0:02:07,000
What I got is basically a gesture-interface device

40
0:02:08.26,000 --> 0:02:11,000
that actually acts as a motion-sensing device

41
0:02:12.26,000 --> 0:02:13,000
made for two dollars.

42
0:02:14.26,000 --> 0:02:16,000
So, here, whatever movement I do in my physical world

43
0:02:17.26,000 --> 0:02:19,000
is actually replicated inside the digital world

44
0:02:20.26,000 --> 0:02:23,000
just using this small device that I made, around eight years back,

45
0:02:23.38,000 --> 0:02:24,000
in 2000.

46
0:02:25.26,000 --> 0:02:27,000
