75
0:03:35.26,000 --> 0:03:36,000
or where you can trash the cup.

76
0:03:37.26,000 --> 0:03:39,000
So, these were some of the earlier explorations I did

77
0:03:40.26,000 --> 0:03:43,000
because the goal was to connect these two worlds seamlessly.

78
0:03:44.26,000 --> 0:03:45,000
Among all these experiments,

79
0:03:46.26,000 --> 0:03:47,000
there was one thing in common:

80
0:03:48.26,000 --> 0:03:51,000
I was trying to bring a part of the physical world

81
0:03:51.789,000 --> 0:03:52,000
to the digital world.

82
0:03:53.311,000 --> 0:03:54,000
I was taking some part of the objects,

83
0:03:55.26,000 --> 0:03:57,000
or any of the intuitiveness of real life,

84
0:03:58.261,000 --> 0:04:,000
and bringing them to the digital world,

85
0:04:00.474,000 --> 0:04:04,000
because the goal was to make our computing interfaces more intuitive.

86
0:04:04.523,000 --> 0:04:08,000
But then I realized that we humans are not actually interested in computing.

87
0:04:09.26,000 --> 0:04:11,000
What we are interested in is information.

88
0:04:12.26,000 --> 0:04:13,000
We want to know about things.

89
0:04:14.26,000 --> 0:04:16,000
We want to know about dynamic things going around.

90
0:04:16.665,000 --> 0:04:2,000
So I thought, around last year -- in the beginning of the last year --

91
0:04:21.26,000 --> 0:04:24,000
I started thinking, "Why can I not take this approach in the reverse way?"

92
0:04:25.379,000 --> 0:04:27,000
Maybe, "How about I take my digital world

93
0:04:27.46,000 --> 0:04:31,000
